{
  "text": "The TIMPs (tissue inhibitors of metalloproteinases) are a family of four endogenous inhibitors that were originally characterized by their ability to inhibit the MMPs (matrix metalloproteinases). TIMPs have now been shown to also inhibit members of two other related metalloproteinase families, the ADAMs (a disintegrin and metalloproteinase) and the ADAMTSs (ADAM with thrombospondin motifs). Specifically, TIMP-1 has been shown to inhibit ADAM10 [CITATION_1] , whereas TIMP-2 has been shown to inhibit ADAM12 [CITATION_2] and ADAMTS-1 [CITATION_3] ; TIMP-3 has the widest inhibitory activity among the TIMPs, since it has been shown to inhibit ADAM10 [CITATION_4] , ADAM12 [CITATION_5] , ADAM17 [CITATION_6] , ADAM28 [CITATION_7] , ADAM33 [CITATION_8] , ADAMTS-1 [CITATION_9] , ADAMTS-2 [CITATION_10] , ADAMTS-4 [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] and ADAMTS-5 [CITATION_13] . Not all ADAMs and ADAMTSs are inhibited by the TIMPs; for example, none of the four human TIMPs inhibits ADAM8 or ADAM9 [CITATION_14] .",
  "correct_citation": {
